@node "Preferences" "Preferences"
@next "Shell"
@prev "Logfile"

                                  @{b}Preferences@{ub}
                              ===================


    @{b}··· PAL WorkBench ···@{ub}

    Here you can choose resolution und depth of the PAL screen you get,
    if you activate the @{"PAL Option" link PAL}.

    @{FG shine}Resolution@{FG text} You can choose between @{b}"Hires"@{ub} and @{b}"Hires Interlace"@{ub}.

    @{FG shine}Depth     @{FG text} You can select from 2 up to 256 Colors. There is no build in
               recognition for AGA or ECS chipset. I think, every owner of
               an amiga today, should know wich chipset he/she owns and how
               many colors can be dipsplayed.

               @{b}"same depth"@{ub} is standard for this option. StartupControl
               uses the selected depth from "screenmode.prefs", your daily
               configuration.



    @{b}··· Shell ···@{ub}

    @{FG shine}o Shell-Buttons@{FG text} you can decide wether StartupControl quits or just
                    runs the shell-process in background

                    If it quits, startup-sequence is holded, until you
                    send a BREAK command to StartupControl by typing

                    @{b}C:Break 1@{ub}

                    after receiving that, startup-sequence (or Standard-Startup)
                    will be continued.

    @{FG shine}o WINDOW@{FG text}        here you can change the outfit of your shell-window.
                    It works like the commandline option WINDOW for
                    doscommand "newshell".

                    eg. WINDOW CON:15/20/610/200/Amiga-Shell/CLOSE//



    @{b}··· General Preferences ···@{ub}

    @{FG shine}o (Un)Lock @{FG text}     if checked, you can use this option


    @{FG shine}o Drives @{FG text}       Sign in all drives you want to protect. Several drives
                    have to be divided by "|".

                    (eg. DH0:|DH1:|DH2:)



    @{FG shine}o Startupfiles@{FG text}  if you often use the "Other Startup" option, you should
                    set this flag, but following has to be done before:

                    o This flag is only available if @{b}S:SC_Startupfiles@{ub} dawer
                      and a file in it called "@{b}Standard-Startup@{ub}" exist.

                    o Make this new drawer in your S: directory and move your
                      startup-sequence into it. Rename it to @{b}Standard-Startup@{ub}.
                      This file will be executed if you don`t choose any other
                      startup-file later on.

                      @{b}REMOVE everything before and including

                      .....
                      C:StartupControl
                      .....

                      command from "Standard-Startup" and @{ub}...

                    o ... make a new startup-sequence with the cuted lines in it:

                      C:SetPatch >NIL:
                      .....
                      <any other thing you want to run before StartupControl>
                      .....
                      C:StartupControl_V2.33
                      C:EndCLI

                    If this is done you can add as much other "startup-sequences"
                    as you want by copying them to @{b}S:SC_Startupfiles@{ub} drawer. When
                    you select "Other Startup" option, StartupControl will now automaticly
                    go into this drawer, where you can select any of them.

                    (This is a better solution for an alternativ startup-sequence. There
                     will be no "dead task" anymore.)


    @{FG shine}o Reqtools@{FG text}      Simply you choose the filerequester you want to see:
                    asl or reqtools!


    @{FG shine}o Logfile@{FG text}       Here you can choose the name and path of a logfile, that StartupControl
                    uses, if you want to save the LastAlert-information.
                    If this logfile already exists, the latest information from @{"Last Alert" link "Last Alert"}
                    will be added to this logfile.

                    eg: ram:SC2_Alerts.log

                    If this logfile is placed on a harddisk, you should have a look
                    at it sometimes. With every saved alert this file will grow up
                    circa 450 bytes.

    @{FG shine}o BattClock@{FG text}     If this flag is set, StartupControl takes a look at the @{"systemtime" link Systemzeit}
                    every bootup. Some gurus lead also to a crash of the batteryclock.
                    If that happened, StartupControl opens a window, where you easily
                    can edit date and time.

    @{FG shine}o Cache Control@{FG text} If this flag is set, you can control the processor @{"cache" link CacheContol}. Set
                    the flags and save preferences to make the cache settings durable.
                    Then StartupControl will set these flags every bootup.


    @{FG shine}o Countdown@{FG text}     This number is an amount of seconds, StartupControl will wait
                    for activation. If it is set to "0", StartupControl acts as in
                    any older version.
                    You can cancel waiting at every time by pressing the @{FG shine}@{b}right@{ub}@{FG text}
                    @{FG shine}@{b}mousebutton@{ub}@{FG text} or @{FG shine}@{b}Escape@{ub}@{FG text}. In that case, the startup-sequence will
                    be continued.


    @{FG shine}o Force Popup @{FG text}  If this switch is set, StartupControl will popup allways. You don`t
                    need to use LMB or the ALT-keys to see the gui.


    @{FG shine}o Easy PAL @{FG text}     When Pal-option is activated, only Workbench Screen
                    will be patchec to PAL. Monitordrivers will be loaded,
                    so you can switch to other resolutions later.

@endnode

